[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data lineage facilitates the ability to replay specific segments or inputs of the dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This can be used in debugging or regenerating lost outputs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In database systems, this concept is closely related to data provenance, which involves maintaining records of inputs, entities, systems and processes that influence data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data provenance provides a historical record of data origins and transformations.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data lineage information includes technical metadata about data transformations.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Enriched data lineage may include additional elements such as data quality test results, reference data, data models, business terminology, data stewardship information, program management details and enterprise systems associated with data points and transformations.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data lineage visualization tools often include masking features that allow users to focus on information relevant to specific use cases.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] To unify representations across disparate systems, metadata normalization or standardization may be required.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Representation broadly depends on the scope of the metadata management and reference point of interest.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data lineage provides sources of the data and intermediate data flow hops from the reference point with **backward data lineage**, leading to the final destination's data points and its intermediate data flows with **forward data lineage**.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] These views can be combined with end-to-end **lineage** for a reference point that provides a complete audit trail of that data point of interest from sources to their final destinations.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] As the data points or hops increase, the complexity of such representation becomes incomprehensible.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Thus, the best feature of the data lineage view is the ability to simplify the view by temporarily masking unwanted peripheral data points.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Tools with the masking feature enable scalability of the view and enhance analysis with the best user experience for both technical and business users.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data lineage also enables companies to trace sources of specific business data to track errors, implement changes in processes and implementing system migrations to save significant amounts of time and resources.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data lineage can improve efficiency in business intelligence BI processes.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data lineage can be represented visually to discover the data flow and movement from its source to destination via various changes and hops on its way in the enterprise environment.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This includes how the data is transformed along the way, how the representation and parameters change and how the data splits or converges after each hop.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] A simple representation of the Data Lineage can be shown with dots and lines, where dots represent data containers for data points, and lines connecting them represent transformations the data undergoes between the data containers.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data lineage can be visualized at various levels based on the granularity of the view.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] At a very high-level, data lineage is visualized as systems that the data interacts with before it reaches its destination.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] At its most granular, visualizations at the data point level can provide the details of the data point and its historical behavior, attribute properties and trends and data quality of the data passed through that specific data point in the data lineage.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The scope of the data lineage determines the volume of metadata required to represent its data lineage.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Usually, data governance and data management of an organization determine the scope of the data lineage based on their regulations, enterprise data management strategy, data impact, reporting attributes and critical data elements of the organization.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Distributed systems like Google Map Reduce, Microsoft Dryad, Apache Hadoop (an open-source project) and Google Pregel provide such platforms for businesses and users.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] However, even with these systems, Big Data analytics can take several hours, days or weeks to run, simply due to the data volumes involved.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] For example, a ratings prediction algorithm for the Netflix Prize challenge took nearly 20 hours to execute on 50 cores, and a large-scale image processing task to estimate geographic information took 3 days to complete using 400 cores.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] "The Large Synoptic Survey Telescope is expected to generate terabytes of data every night and eventually store more than 50 petabytes, while in the bioinformatics sector, the 12 largest genome sequencing houses in the world now store petabytes of data apiece.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] It is very difficult for a data scientist to trace an unknown or an unanticipated result.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Big data analytics is the process of examining large data sets to uncover hidden patterns, unknown correlations, market trends, customer preferences and other useful business information.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Machine learning, among other algorithms, is used to transform and analyze the data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Due to the large size of the data, there could be unknown features in the data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The massive scale and unstructured nature of data, the complexity of these analytics pipelines, and long runtimes pose significant manageability and debugging challenges.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Even a single error in these analytics can be extremely difficult to identify and remove.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] While one may debug them by re-running the entire analytics through a debugger for stepwise debugging, this can be expensive due to the amount of time and resources needed.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Auditing and data validation are other major problems due to the growing ease of access to relevant data sources for use in experiments, the sharing of data between scientific communities and use of third-party data in business enterprises.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] As such, more cost-efficient ways of analyzing data intensive scale-able computing (DISC) are crucial to their continued effective use.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] According to an EMC/IDC study, 2.8 ZB of data were created and replicated in 2012.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Furthermore, the same study states that the digital universe will double every two years between now and 2020, and that there will be approximately 5.2 TB of data for every person in 2020.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Based on current technology, the storage of this much data will mean greater energy usage by data centers.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Unstructured data usually refers to information that doesn't reside in a traditional row-column database.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Unstructured data files often include text and multimedia content, such as e-mail messages, word processing documents, videos, photos, audio files, presentations, web pages and many other kinds of business documents.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] While these types of files may have an internal structure, they are still considered "unstructured" because the data they contain doesn't fit neatly into a database.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The amount of unstructured data in enterprises is growing many times faster than structured databases are growing.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Big data can include both structured and unstructured data, but IDC estimates that 90 percent of Big Data is unstructured data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The fundamental challenge of unstructured data sources is that they are difficult for non-technical business users and data analysts alike to unbox, understand and prepare for analytic use.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Beyond issues of structure, the sheer volume of this type of data contributes to such difficulty.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Because of this, current data mining techniques often leave out valuable information and make analyzing unstructured data laborious and expensive.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In today's competitive business environment, companies have to find and analyze the relevant data they need quickly.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The challenge is going through the volumes of data and accessing the level of detail needed, all at a high speed.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The challenge only grows as the degree of granularity increases.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Some vendors are using increased memory and parallel processing to crunch large volumes of data quickly.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Another method is putting data in-memory but using a grid computing approach, where many machines are used to solve a problem.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Both approaches allow organizations to explore huge data volumes.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Even with this level of sophisticated hardware and software, a few of the image processing tasks in large scale take a few days to few weeks.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Debugging of the data processing is extremely hard due to long run times.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] A third approach of advanced data discovery solutions combines self-service data prep with visual data discovery, enabling analysts to simultaneously prepare and visualize data side-by-side in an interactive analysis environment offered by newer companies, such as Trifacta, Alteryx and others.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Another method to track data lineage is spreadsheet programs such as Excel that offer users cell-level lineage, or the ability to see which cells are dependent on another.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] However, the structure of the transformation is lost.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Similarly, ETL or mapping software provide transform-level lineage, yet this view typically doesn't display data and is too coarse-grained to distinguish between transforms that are logically independent (e.g. transforms that operate on distinct columns) or dependent.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Big Data platforms have a very complicated structure, where data is distributed across a vast range.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Typically, the jobs are mapped into several machines and results are later combined by the reduce operations.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Debugging a Big Data pipeline becomes very challenging due to the very nature of the system.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] It will not be an easy task for the data scientist to figure out which machine's data has outliers and unknown features causing a particular algorithm to give unexpected results.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data provenance or data lineage can be used to make the debugging of Big Data pipeline easier.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This necessitates the collection of data about data transformations.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The below section will explain data provenance in more detail.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In information systems, **data provenance** is information about the entities, activities, and agents involved in producing a piece of data; it records how data was derived and can be used to assess quality, reliability, and trustworthiness.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Classical database research distinguishes **why**, **where**, and **how** provenance and shows how these forms support tasks such as query debugging, view maintenance, confidence estimation, and annotation propagation.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In scientific workflows, provenance documents the derivation history from original sources through workflow steps, supporting reproducibility and reuse of results.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Open, implementation-oriented specifications such as **OpenLineage** model lineage in terms of jobs, runs, and datasets to enable automated capture from modern data pipelines.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Provenance is information about entities, activities and people involved in producing a piece of data or thing, which can be used to form assessments about its quality, reliability or trustworthiness.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] is defined as a record that describes the people, institutions, entities and activities involved in producing, influencing, or delivering a piece of data or something.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In particular, the provenance of information is crucial in deciding whether information is to be trusted, how it should be integrated with other diverse information sources, and how to give credit to its originators when reusing it.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In an open and inclusive environment such as the Web, where users find information that is often contradictory or questionable, provenance can help those users to make trust judgements.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Intuitively, for an operator T producing output o , lineage consists of triplets of form $\{i,T,o\}$ , where i is the set of inputs to T used to derive o .
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] A query that finds the inputs deriving an output is called a *backward tracing query*, while one that finds the outputs produced by an input is called a *forward tracing query*.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Backward tracing is useful for debugging, while forward tracing is useful for tracking error propagation.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Tracing queries also form the basis for replaying an original dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] However, to efficiently use lineage in a DISC system, we need to be able to capture lineage at multiple levels (or granularities) of operators and data, capture accurate lineage for DISC processing constructs and be able to trace through multiple dataflow stages efficiently.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] A DISC system consists of several levels of operators and data, and different use cases of lineage can dictate the level at which lineage needs to be captured.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Lineage can be captured at the level of the job, using files and giving lineage tuples of form {IF i, M RJob, OF i }, lineage can also be captured at the level of each task, using records and giving, for example, lineage tuples of form {(k rr, v rr ), map, (k m, v m )}.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The first form of lineage is called coarse-grain lineage, while the second form is called fine-grain lineage.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Integrating lineage across different granularities enables users to ask questions such as "Which file read by a MapReduce job produced this particular output record?" and can be useful in debugging across different operators and data granularities within a dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] To capture end-to-end lineage in a DISC system, we use the Ibis model, which introduces the notion of containment hierarchies for operators and data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Specifically, Ibis proposes that an operator can be contained within another and such a relationship between two operators is called *operator containment*.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Operator containment implies that the contained (or child) operator performs a part of the logical operation of the containing (or parent) operator.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] For example, a MapReduce task is contained in a job.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Similar containment relationships exist for data as well, Known as data containment.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data containment implies that the contained data is a subset of the containing data (superset).
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Data lineage systems can be categorized as either eager or lazy.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Eager collection systems capture the entire lineage of the data flow at run time.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The kind of lineage they capture may be coarse-grain or fine-grain, but they do not require any further computations on the data flow after its execution.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Lazy lineage collection typically captures only coarse-grain lineage at run time.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] These systems incur low capture overheads due to the small amount of lineage they capture.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] However, to answer fine-grain tracing queries, they must replay the data flow on all (or a large part) of its input and collect fine-grain lineage during the replay.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This approach is suitable for forensic systems, where a user wants to debug an observed bad output.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Eager fine-grain lineage collection systems incur higher capture overheads than lazy collection systems.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] However, they enable sophisticated replay and debugging.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] An actor is an entity that transforms data; it may be a Dryad vertex, individual map and reduce operators, a MapReduce job, or an entire dataflow pipeline.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Actors act as black boxes and the inputs and outputs of an actor are tapped to capture lineage in the form of associations, where an association is a triplet $\{i,T,o\}$ that relates an input i with an output o for an actor T .
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The instrumentation thus captures lineage in a dataflow one actor at a time, piecing it into a set of associations for each actor.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The system developer needs to capture the data an actor reads (from other actors) and the data an actor writes (to other actors).
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] For example, a developer can treat the Hadoop Job Tracker as an actor by recording the set of files read and written by each job.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Association is a combination of the inputs, outputs and the operation itself.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The operation is represented in terms of a black box also known as the actor.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The associations describe the transformations that are applied to the data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The associations are stored in the association tables.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Each unique actor is represented by its association table.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] An association itself looks like {i, T, o} where i is the set of inputs to the actor T and o is the set of outputs produced by the actor.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Associations are the basic units of Data Lineage.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Individual associations are later clubbed together to construct the entire history of transformations that were applied to the data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Big data systems increase capacity by adding new hardware or software entities into the distributed system.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This process is called *horizontal scaling*.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The distributed system acts as a single entity at the logical level even though it comprises multiple hardware and software entities.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The system should continue to maintain this property after horizontal scaling.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] An important advantage of horizontal scalability is that it can provide the ability to increase capacity on the fly.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The biggest plus point is that horizontal scaling can be done using commodity hardware.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The horizontal scaling feature of Big Data systems should be taken into account while creating the architecture of lineage store.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This is essential because the lineage store itself should also be able to scale in parallel with the Big Data system.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The number of associations and amount of storage required to store lineage will increase with the increase in size and capacity of the system.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The architecture of Big Data systems makes use of a single lineage store not appropriate and impossible to scale.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The immediate solution to this problem is to distribute the lineage store itself.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The best-case scenario is to use a local lineage store for every machine in the distributed system network.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This allows the lineage store also to scale horizontally.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In this design, the lineage of data transformations applied to the data on a particular machine is stored on the local lineage store of that specific machine.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The lineage store typically stores association tables.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Each actor is represented by its own association table.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The rows are the associations themselves, and the columns represent inputs and outputs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] It allows horizontal scaling of the lineage store.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] If a single centralized lineage store was used, then this information had to be carried over the network, which would cause additional network latency.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The network latency is also avoided by the use of a distributed lineage store.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The information stored in terms of associations needs to be combined by some means to get the data flow of a particular job.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In a distributed system a job is broken down into multiple tasks.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] One or more instances run a particular task.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The results produced on these individual machines are later combined to finish the job.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Tasks running on different machines perform multiple transformations on the data in the machine.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] All the transformations applied to the data on a machine is stored in the local lineage store of that machines.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This information needs to be combined to get the lineage of the entire job.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The lineage of the entire job should help the data scientist understand the data flow of the job and he/she can use the data flow to debug the Big Data pipeline.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The data flow is reconstructed in 3 stages.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The first stage of the data flow reconstruction is the computation of the association tables.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The association tables exist for each actor in each local lineage store.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The entire association table for an actor can be computed by combining these individual association tables.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This is generally done using a series of equality joins based on the actors themselves.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In few scenarios the tables might also be joined using inputs as the key.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Indexes can also be used to improve the efficiency of a join.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The joined tables need to be stored on a single instance or a machine to further continue processing.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] There are multiple schemes that are used to pick a machine where a join would be computed.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The easiest one being the one with minimum CPU load.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Space constraints should also be kept in mind while picking the instance where join would happen.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The second step in data flow reconstruction is computing an association graph from the lineage information.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The graph represents the steps in the data flow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The actors act as vertices and the associations act as edges.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Each actor T is linked to its upstream and downstream actors in the data flow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] An upstream actor of T is one that produced the input of T, while a downstream actor is one that consumes the output of T.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Containment relationships are always considered while creating the links.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The graph consists of three types of links or edges.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The simplest link is an explicitly specified link between two actors.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] These links are explicitly specified in the code of a machine learning algorithm.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] When an actor is aware of its exact upstream or downstream actor, it can communicate this information to lineage API.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This information is later used to link these actors during the tracing query.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] For example, in the MapReduce architecture, each map instance knows the exact record reader instance whose output it consumes.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Developers can attach data flow archetypes to each logical actor.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] A data flow archetype explains how the child types of an actor type arrange themselves in a data flow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] With the help of this information, one can infer a link between each actor of a source type and a destination type.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] For example, in the MapReduce architecture, the map actor type is the source for reduce, and vice versa.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The system infers this from the data flow archetypes and duly links map instances with reduce instances.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] However, there may be several MapReduce jobs in the data flow and linking all map instances with all reduce instances can create false links.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] To prevent this, such links are restricted to actor instances contained within a common actor instance of a containing (or parent) actor type.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Thus, map and reduce instances are only linked to each other if they belong to the same job.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In distributed systems, sometimes there are implicit links, which are not specified during execution.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] For example, an implicit link exists between an actor that wrote to a file and another actor that read from it.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Such links connect actors which use a common data set for execution.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The dataset is the output of the first actor and the input of the actor follows it.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The final step in the data flow reconstruction is the topological sorting of the association graph.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The directed graph created in the previous step is topologically sorted to obtain the order in which the actors have modified the data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This record of modifications by the different actors involved is used to track the data flow of the Big Data pipeline or task.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This is the most crucial step in Big Data debugging.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The captured lineage is combined and processed to obtain the data flow of the pipeline.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The data flow helps the data scientist or a developer to look deeply into the actors and their transformations.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This step allows the data scientist to figure out the part of the algorithm that is generating the unexpected output.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] A Big Data pipeline can go wrong in two broad ways.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The first is a presence of a suspicious actor in the dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The second is the existence of outliers in the data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The first case can be debugged by tracing the dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] By using lineage and data-flow information together a data scientist can figure out how the inputs are converted into outputs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] During the process actors that behave unexpectedly can be caught.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Either these actors can be removed from the data flow, or they can be augmented by new actors to change the dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The improved dataflow can be replayed to test the validity of it.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Debugging faulty actors include recursively performing coarse-grain replay on actors in the dataflow, which can be expensive in resources for long dataflows.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Another approach is to manually inspect lineage logs to find anomalies, which can be tedious and time-consuming across several stages of a dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Furthermore, these approaches work only when the data scientist can discover bad outputs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] To debug analytics without known bad outputs, the data scientist needs to analyze the dataflow for suspicious behavior in general.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] However, often, a user may not know the expected normal behavior and cannot specify predicates.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This section describes a debugging methodology for retrospectively analyzing lineage to identify faulty actors in a multi-stage dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] We believe that sudden changes in an actor's behavior, such as its average selectivity, processing rate or output size, is characteristic of an anomaly.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Lineage can reflect such changes in actor behavior over time and across different actor instances.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Thus, mining lineage to identify such changes can be useful in debugging faulty actors in a dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The second problem i.e. the existence of outliers can also be identified by running the dataflow step wise and looking at the transformed outputs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The data scientist finds a subset of outputs that are not in accordance with the rest of outputs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The inputs which are causing these bad outputs are outliers in the data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This problem can be solved by removing the set of outliers from the data and replaying the entire dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] It can also be solved by modifying the machine learning algorithm by adding, removing or moving actors in the dataflow.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The changes in the dataflow are successful if the replayed dataflow does not produce bad outputs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Although the utilization of data lineage methodologies represents a novel approach to the debugging of Big Data pipelines, the process is not straightforward.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] A number of challenges must be addressed, including the scalability of the lineage store, the fault tolerance of the lineage store, the accurate capture of lineage for black box operators, and numerous other considerations.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] These challenges must be carefully evaluated in order to develop a realistic design for data lineage capture, taking into account the inherent trade-offs between them.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] DISC systems are primarily batch processing systems designed for high throughput.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] They execute several jobs per analytics, with several tasks per job.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The overall number of operators executing at any time in a cluster can range from hundreds to thousands depending on the cluster size.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Lineage capture for these systems must be able scale to both large volumes of data and numerous operators to avoid being a bottleneck for the DISC analytics.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Lineage capture systems must also be fault tolerant to avoid rerunning data flows to capture lineage.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] At the same time, they must also accommodate failures in the DISC system.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] To do so, they must be able to identify a failed DISC task and avoid storing duplicate copies of lineage between the partial lineage generated by the failed task and duplicate lineage produced by the restarted task.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] A lineage system should also be able to gracefully handle multiple instances of local lineage systems going down.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This can be achieved by storing replicas of lineage associations in multiple machines.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] The replica can act like a backup in the event of the real copy being lost.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Lineage systems for DISC dataflows must be able to capture accurate lineage across black-box operators to enable fine-grain debugging.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Although producing highly accurate lineage, such techniques can incur significant time overheads for capture or tracing, and it may be preferable to instead trade some accuracy for better performance.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage collection system for DISC dataflows that can capture lineage from arbitrary operators with reasonable accuracy, and without significant overheads in capture or tracing.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Tracing is essential for debugging, during which a user can issue multiple tracing queries.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Thus, it is important that tracing has fast turnaround times.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Ikeda et al. can perform efficient backward tracing queries for MapReduce dataflows but are not generic to different DISC systems and do not perform efficient forward queries.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Lipstick, a lineage system for Pig, while able to perform both backward and forward tracing, is specific to Pig and SQL operators and can only perform coarse-grain tracing for black-box operators.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage system that enables efficient forward and backward tracing for generic DISC systems and dataflows with black-box operators.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Replaying only specific inputs or portions of dataflow is crucial for efficient debugging and simulating what-if scenarios.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Ikeda et al. present a methodology for a lineage-based refresh, which selectively replays updated inputs to recompute affected outputs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] This is useful during debugging for re-computing outputs when a bad input has been fixed.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] However, sometimes a user may want to remove the bad input and replay the lineage of outputs previously affected by the error to produce error-free outputs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Another use of replay in debugging involves replaying bad inputs for stepwise debugging (called selective replay).
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Current approaches to using lineage in DISC systems do not address these.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Thus, there is a need for a lineage system that can perform both exclusive and selective replays to address different debugging needs.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] One of the primary debugging concerns in DISC systems is identifying faulty operators.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] In long dataflows with several hundreds of operators or tasks, manual inspection can be tedious and prohibitive.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] Even if lineage is used to narrow the subset of operators to examine, the lineage of a single output can still span several operators.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-lineage] There is a need for an inexpensive automated debugging system, which can substantially narrow the set of potentially faulty operators, with reasonable accuracy, to minimize the amount of manual examination required.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] As early as 1985, researchers recognized the need for defining timing attributes in database tables, which would be necessary for tracking changes to databases.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] This research continued into the 1990s, and the theory was formalized into practical methods for managing data in relational databases, providing some of the foundational concepts for what would later become data version control.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] In the early 2010s the size of data sets was rapidly expanding, and relational databases were no longer sufficient to manage the amounts of data organizations were accumulating.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] The rise of the Apache Hadoop eco system, with HDFS as a storage layer, and later object storage had become dominant in big data operations.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Research into data management tools and data version control systems increased sharply, along with demand for such tools from both academia and the private and public sectors.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] The first versioned database was proposed in 2012 for the SciDB database, and demonstrated it was possible to create chains and trees of different versions of the database while decreasing both the overall storage size and access speeds associated with previous methods.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] In 2014, a proposal was made to generalize these principles into a platform that could be used for any application.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] In 2016, a prototype for a data version control system was developed during a Kaggle competition.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] This software was later used internally at an AI firm, and eventually spun off as a startup.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Since then, a number of data version control systems, both open and closed source, have been developed and offered commercially, with a subset dedicated specifically to machine learning.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] A wide range of scientific disciplines have adopted automated analysis of large quantities of data, including astrophysics, seismology, biology and medicine, social sciences and economics, and many other fields.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] The principle of reproducibility is an important aspect of formalizing findings in scientific disciplines, and in the context of data science presents a number of challenges.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Most datasets are constantly changing, whether due to the addition of more data or changes in the structure and format of the data, and small changes can have significant effects on the outcome of experiments.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Data version control allows for recording the exact state of data sets at a particular moment of time, making it easier to reproduce and understand experimental outcomes.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] If data practitioners can only know the present state of the data, they may run into a number of challenges such as difficulties in problem debugging or complying with data audits.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Data version control is sometimes used in testing and development of applications that interact with large quantities of data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Some data version control tools allow users to create replicas of their production environment for testing purposes.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] This approach allows them to test data integration processes such as extract, transform and load (ETL) and understand the changes made to data without having a negative impact on the consumers of the production data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] In the context of machine learning, data version control can be used for optimizing the performance of models.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] It can allow automating the process of analyzing outcomes with different versions of a data set to continuously improve performance.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] It is possible that open source data version control software could eliminate the need for proprietary AI platforms by extending tools like Git and CI/CD for use by machine learning engineers.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Many open-source solutions build on Git-like semantics to provide these capabilities, as Git itself was designed for small text files and doesn't support typical machine learning datasets, which are very large.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] CI/CD methodologies can be applied to datasets using data version control.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Version control enables users to integrate with automation servers that allow establishing a CI/CD process for data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] By adding testing platforms to the process, they can guarantee high quality of the data product.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] In this scenario, teams execute Continuous Integration (CI) tests on data and set checks in place to ensure the data is promoted to production only all the set data quality and data governance criteria are met.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] To experiment on a dataset without impacting production data, one can use data version control to create replicas of the production environment where tests can be carried out.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Such replicas allow testing and understanding of changes safely applied to data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Data version control tools allow replication environments without the time- and resource-consuming maintenance.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Instead, such tools allow objects to be shared using metadata.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Continuous changes in data sets can sometimes cause functionality issues or lead to undesired outcomes, especially when applications are using the data.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] Data version control tools allow for the possibility to roll back a data set to an earlier state.
[src:dvc-versioning/data-version-control] This can be used to restore or improve functionality of an application or to correct errors or bad data which has been mistakenly included.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Design goals of Git include speed, data integrity, and support for distributed, non-linear workflows—thousands of parallel branches running on different computers.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] As with most other distributed version control systems, and unlike most client–server systems, Git maintains a local copy of the entire repository, also known as the "repo", with history and version-tracking abilities, independent of network access or a central server.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] A repository is stored on each computer in a standard directory with additional, hidden files to provide version control capabilities.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git provides features to synchronize changes between repositories that share history; for asynchronous collaboration, this extends to repositories on remote machines.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Although all repositories (with the same history) are peers, developers often use a central server to host a repository to hold an integrated copy.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Today, Git is the version control system most commonly used by software developers.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] It is the most popular distributed version control system, with nearly 95% of developers reporting it as their primary version control system as of 2022.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] It is the most widely used source-code management tool among professional developers.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Several different software forges offer Git repository services, including GitHub, SourceForge, Bitbucket and GitLab.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git is free and open-source software shared under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The trademark "Git" is registered by the Software Freedom Conservancy.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Torvalds started developing Git in April 2005 after the free license for BitKeeper, the proprietary source-control management (SCM) system used for Linux kernel development since 2002, was revoked for Linux.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The copyright holder of BitKeeper, Larry McVoy, claimed that Andrew Tridgell had created SourcePuller by reverse engineering the BitKeeper protocols.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The same incident also spurred the creation of Mercurial, another version-control system.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Torvalds wanted a distributed system that he could use like BitKeeper, but none of the available free systems met his needs.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] He cited an example of a source-control management system needing 30 seconds to apply a patch and update all associated metadata, and noted that this would not scale to the needs of Linux kernel development, where synchronizing with fellow maintainers could require 250 such actions at once.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] These criteria eliminated every version-control system in use at the time, so immediately after the 2.6.12-rc2 Linux kernel development release, Torvalds set out to write his own.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The development of Git began on 3 April 2005.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Torvalds announced the project on 6 April and became self-hosting the next day.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The first merge of multiple branches took place on 18 April.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Torvalds achieved his performance goals; on 29 April, the nascent Git was benchmarked recording patches to the Linux kernel tree at a rate of 6.7 patches per second.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] On 16 June, Git managed the kernel 2.6.12 release.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Torvalds turned over maintenance on 26 July 2005 to Junio Hamano, a major contributor to the project.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Hamano was responsible for the 1.0 release on 21 December 2005.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Torvalds quipped about the name *git* (which is British English slang for an unpleasant or silly person): "I'm an egotistical bastard, and I name all my projects after myself.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] First 'Linux', now 'git'." The man page describes Git as "the stupid content tracker".
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The source code for Git refers to the program as "the information manager from hell".
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git's design is a synthesis of Torvalds's experience with Linux in maintaining a large distributed development project, along with his intimate knowledge of file-system performance gained from the same project and the urgent need to produce a working system in short order.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git supports rapid branching and merging, and includes specific tools for visualizing and navigating a non-linear development history.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] In Git, a core assumption is that a change will be merged more often than it is written, as it is passed around to various reviewers.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] In Git, branches are very lightweight: a branch is only a reference to one commit.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] , Git gives each developer a local copy of the full development history, and changes are copied from one such repository to another.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] These changes are imported as added development branches and can be merged in the same way as a locally developed branch.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git also has a CVS server emulation, which enables the use of existing CVS clients and IDE plugins to access Git repositories.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] repositories can be used directly with git-svn.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] ; fetching version history from a locally stored repository can be one hundred times faster than fetching it from the remote server.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] in Git terms) depends upon the complete development history leading up to that commit.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Once it is published, it is not possible to change the old versions without it being noticed.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] , but with added data at the nodes and leaves.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] and several shell scripts that provide wrappers around those programs.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Although most of those scripts have since been rewritten in C for speed and portability, the design remains, and it is easy to chain the components together.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] As part of its toolkit design, Git has a well-defined model of an incomplete merge, and it has multiple algorithms for completing it, culminating in telling the user that it is unable to complete the merge automatically and that manual editing is needed.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Aborting operations or backing out changes will leave useless dangling objects in the database.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] These are generally a small fraction of the continuously growing history of wanted objects.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] when enough loose objects have been created in the repository.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git stores each newly created object as a separate file.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Although individually compressed, this takes up a great deal of space and is inefficient.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] that files with the same name are probably similar, without depending on this for correctness.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] A corresponding index file is created for each packfile, recording the offset of each object in the packfile.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Newly created objects (with newly added history) are still stored as single objects, and periodic repacking is needed to maintain space efficiency.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The process of packing the repository can be very computationally costly.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] By allowing objects to exist in the repository in a loose but quickly generated format, Git allows the costly pack operation to be deferred until later, when time matters less, e.g., the end of a workday.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] inside, and the file name of the packfile also contains an SHA-1 checksum.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Another property of Git is that it snapshots directory trees of files.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The earliest systems for tracking versions of source code, Source Code Control System (SCCS) and Revision Control System (RCS), worked on individual files and emphasized the space savings to be gained from interleaved deltas (SCCS) or delta encoding (RCS) the (mostly similar) versions.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Later revision-control systems maintained this notion of a file having an identity across multiple revisions of a project.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] However, Torvalds rejected this concept.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Consequently, Git does not explicitly record file revision relationships at any level below the source-code tree.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git's primitives are not inherently a source-code management system.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] From this initial design approach, Git has developed the full set of features expected of a traditional SCM, with features mostly being created as needed, then refined and extended over time.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git has two data structures: a mutable *index* (also called *stage* or *cache*) that caches information about the working directory and the next revision to be committed; and an *object database* that stores immutable objects.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The index serves as a connection point between the object database and the working tree.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Each object is identified by a SHA-1 hash of its contents.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git computes the hash and uses this value for the object's name.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The object is put into a directory matching the first two characters of its hash.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The rest of the hash is used as the file name for that object.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git stores each revision of a file as a unique blob.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The relationships between the blobs can be found through examining the tree and commit objects.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Newly added objects are stored in their entirety using zlib compression.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] This can consume a large amount of disk space quickly, so objects can be combined into *packs*, which use delta compression to save space, storing blobs as their changes relative to other blobs.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Additionally, Git stores labels called refs (short for references) to indicate the locations of various commits.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] A *.gitignore* file may be created in a Git repository as a plain text file.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The files listed in the *.gitignore* file will *not* be tracked by Git.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] This feature can be used to ignore files with keys or passwords, various extraneous files, and large files (which GitHub will refuse to upload).
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Every object in the Git database that is not referred to may be cleaned up by using a garbage collection command or automatically.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] An object may be referenced by another object or an explicit reference.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The commands to create, move, and delete references vary.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git (the main implementation in C) is primarily developed on Linux, although it also supports most major operating systems, including the BSDs (DragonFly BSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, and OpenBSD), Solaris, macOS, and Windows.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The first Windows port of Git was primarily a Linux-emulation framework that hosts the Linux version.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Currently, native Windows builds of Git are distributed as 32- and 64-bit installers.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The git official website currently maintains a build of Git for Windows, still using the MSYS2 environment.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The JGit implementation of Git is a pure Java software library, designed to be embedded in any Java application.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] JGit is used in the Gerrit code-review tool, and in EGit, a Git client for the Eclipse IDE.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Go-git is an open-source implementation of Git written in pure Go.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] It is currently used for backing projects as a SQL interface for Git code repositories and providing encryption for Git.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Dulwich is an implementation of Git written in pure Python with support for CPython 3.6 and later and Pypy.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The libgit2 implementation of Git is an ANSI C software library with no other dependencies, which can be built on multiple platforms, including Windows, Linux, macOS, and BSD.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] It has bindings for many programming languages, including Ruby, Python, and Haskell.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] As Git is a distributed version control system, it could be used as a server out of the box.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] It is shipped with a built-in command `git daemon` which starts a simple TCP server running on the Git protocol.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Dedicated Git HTTP servers help (amongst other features) by adding access control, displaying the contents of a Git repository via the web interfaces, and managing multiple repositories.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Already existing Git repositories can be cloned and shared to be used by others as a centralized repo.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] It can also be accessed via remote shell just by having the Git software installed and allowing a user to log in.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git servers typically listen on TCP port 9418.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] For Web-based repository browsing, Git is also shipped with gitweb, a CGI-based interface for viewing repository contents over HTTP.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] There are many offerings of Git repositories as a service.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The most popular are GitHub, SourceForge, Bitbucket and GitLab.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git GUI clients offer a graphical user interface (GUI) to simplify interaction with Git repositories.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] These GUIs provide visual representations of project history, including branches, commits, and file changes.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] They also streamline actions like staging changes, creating commits, and managing branches.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Visual diff tools help resolve merge conflicts arising from concurrent development.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git comes with a Tcl/Tk GUI, which allows users to perform actions such as creating and amending commits, creating and merging branches, and interacting with remote repositories.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] In addition to the official GUI, many third-party interfaces exist that provide similar features to the official GUI distributed with Git.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] GUI clients make Git easier to learn and use, improving workflow efficiency and reducing errors.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Open-source directory Open Hub reported a similar uptake among open-source projects.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git was the overwhelming favorite of responding developers in these surveys, reporting as high as 93.9% in 2022.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The UK IT jobs website itjobswatch.co.uk reports that as of late September 2016, 29.27% of UK permanent software development job openings have cited Git, ahead of 12.17% for Microsoft Team Foundation Server, 10.60% for Subversion, 1.30% for Mercurial, and 0.48% for Visual SourceSafe.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] There are many *Git extensions*, like Git LFS, which started as an extension to Git in the GitHub community and is now widely used by other repositories.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Extensions are usually independently developed and maintained by different people, but at some point in the future, a widely used extension can be merged with Git.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Microsoft developed the Virtual File System for Git (VFS for Git; formerly Git Virtual File System or GVFS) extension to handle the size of the Windows source-code tree as part of their 2017 migration from Perforce.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] VFS for Git allows cloned repositories to use placeholders whose contents are downloaded only once a file is accessed.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git can be used in a variety of different ways, but some conventions are commonly adopted.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git does not provide access-control mechanisms, but was designed for operation with other tools that specialize in access control.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] On 17 December 2014, an exploit was found affecting the Windows and macOS versions of the Git client.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] An attacker could also modify the *.git/config* configuration file, which allows the attacker to create malicious Git aliases (aliases for Git commands or external commands) or modify extant aliases to execute malicious commands when run.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The vulnerability was patched in version 2.2.1 of Git, released on 17 December 2014, and announced the next day.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Git version 2.6.1, released on 29 September 2015, contained a patch for a security vulnerability (CVE-2015-7545) that allowed arbitrary code execution.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] The vulnerability was exploitable if an attacker could convince a victim to clone a specific URL, as the arbitrary commands were embedded in the URL.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] An attacker could use the exploit via a man-in-the-middle attack if the connection was unencrypted, as they could redirect the user to a URL of their choice.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Recursive clones were also vulnerable, since they allowed the controller of a repository to specify arbitrary URLs via the gitmodules file.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Linus Torvalds has responded that the hash was mostly to guard against accidental corruption, and the security a cryptographically secure hash gives was just an accidental side effect, with the main security being signing elsewhere.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] Since a demonstration of the SHAttered attack against Git in 2017, Git was modified to use an SHA-1 variant resistant to this attack.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] A plan for hash function transition is being written since February 2020.
[src:dvc-versioning/git] "Git" is a registered word trademark of Software Freedom Conservancy, registered with the United States Patent and Trademark Office as Registration Number 4680534 since 2015-02-03.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:dvc-versioning/pipeline-computing] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The first to stress the importance of reproducibility in science was the Anglo-Irish chemist Robert Boyle, in England in the 17th century.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Boyle's air pump was designed to generate and study vacuum, which at the time was a very controversial concept.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Indeed, distinguished philosophers such as René Descartes and Thomas Hobbes denied the very possibility of vacuum existence.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Historians of science Steven Shapin and Simon Schaffer, in their 1985 book *Leviathan and the Air-Pump*, describe the debate between Boyle and Hobbes, ostensibly over the nature of vacuum, as fundamentally an argument about how useful knowledge should be gained.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Boyle, a pioneer of the experimental method, maintained that the foundations of knowledge should be constituted by experimentally produced facts, which can be made believable to a scientific community by their reproducibility.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] By repeating the same experiment over and over again, Boyle argued, the certainty of fact will emerge.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The air pump, which in the 17th century was a complicated and expensive apparatus to build, also led to one of the first documented disputes over the reproducibility of a particular scientific phenomenon.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In the 1660s, the Dutch scientist Christiaan Huygens built his own air pump in Amsterdam, the first one outside the direct management of Boyle and his assistant at the time Robert Hooke.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Huygens reported an effect he termed "anomalous suspension", in which water appeared to levitate in a glass jar inside his air pump (in fact suspended over an air bubble), but Boyle and Hooke could not replicate this phenomenon in their own pumps.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] As Shapin and Schaffer describe, "it became clear that unless the phenomenon could be produced in England with one of the two pumps available, then no one in England would accept the claims Huygens had made, or his competence in working the pump".
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Huygens was finally invited to England in 1663, and under his personal guidance Hooke was able to replicate anomalous suspension of water.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Following this Huygens was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] However, Shapin and Schaffer also note that "the accomplishment of replication was dependent on contingent acts of judgment.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] One cannot write down a formula saying when replication was or was not achieved".
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The philosopher of science Karl Popper noted briefly in his famous 1934 book *The Logic of Scientific Discovery* that "non-reproducible single occurrences are of no significance to science".
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Such assertions express a common dogma in modern science that reproducibility is a necessary condition (although not necessarily sufficient) for establishing a scientific fact, and in practice for establishing scientific authority in any field of knowledge.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] However, as noted above by Shapin and Schaffer, this dogma is not well-formulated quantitatively, such as statistical significance for instance, and therefore it is not explicitly established how many times must a fact be replicated to be considered reproducible.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Two major steps are naturally distinguished in connection with reproducibility of experimental or observational studies: when new data are obtained in the attempt to achieve it, the term *replicability* is often used, and the new study is a *replication* or *replicate* of the original one.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Obtaining the same results when analyzing the data set of the original study again with the same procedures, many authors use the term *reproducibility* in a narrow, technical sense coming from its use in computational research.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] *Repeatability* is related to the *repetition* of the experiment within the same study by the same researchers.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Reproducibility in the original, wide sense is only acknowledged if a replication performed by an *independent researcher team* is successful.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The terms reproducibility and replicability sometimes appear even in the scientific literature with reversed meaning, as different research fields settled on their own definitions for the same terms.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In chemistry, the terms reproducibility and repeatability are used with a specific quantitative meaning.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In inter-laboratory experiments, a concentration or other quantity of a chemical substance is measured repeatedly in different laboratories to assess the variability of the measurements.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Then, the standard deviation of the difference between two values obtained within the same laboratory is called repeatability.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The standard deviation for the difference between two measurement from different laboratories is called *reproducibility*.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] These measures are related to the more general concept of variance components in metrology.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The term *reproducible research* refers to the idea that scientific results should be documented in such a way that their deduction is fully transparent.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] This requires a detailed description of the methods used to obtain the data and making the full dataset and the code to calculate the results easily accessible.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] This is the essential part of open science.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] To make any research project computationally reproducible, general practice involves all data and files being clearly separated, labelled, and documented.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] All operations should be fully documented and automated as much as practicable, avoiding manual intervention where feasible.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The workflow should be designed as a sequence of smaller steps that are combined so that the intermediate outputs from one step directly feed as inputs into the next step.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Version control should be used as it lets the history of the project be easily reviewed and allows for the documenting and tracking of changes in a transparent manner.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] A basic workflow for reproducible research involves data acquisition, data processing and data analysis.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Data acquisition primarily consists of obtaining primary data from a primary source such as surveys, field observations, experimental research, or obtaining data from an existing source.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Data processing involves the processing and review of the raw data collected in the first stage, and includes data entry, data manipulation and filtering and may be done using software.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The data should be digitized and prepared for data analysis.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Data may be analysed with the use of software to interpret or visualise statistics or data to produce the desired results of the research such as quantitative results including figures and tables.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The use of software and automation enhances the reproducibility of research methods.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] There are systems that facilitate such documentation, like the R Markdown language or the Jupyter notebook.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The Open Science Framework provides a platform and useful tools to support reproducible research.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Psychology has seen a renewal of internal concerns about irreproducible results (see the entry on replicability crisis for empirical results on success rates of replications).
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Researchers showed in a 2006 study that, of 141 authors of a publication from the American Psychological Association (APA) empirical articles, 103 (73%) did not respond with their data over a six-month period.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In a follow-up study published in 2015, it was found that 246 out of 394 contacted authors of papers in APA journals did not share their data upon request (62%).
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In a 2012 paper, it was suggested that researchers should publish data along with their works, and a dataset was released alongside as a demonstration.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In 2017, an article published in *Scientific Data* suggested that this may not be sufficient and that the whole analysis context should be disclosed.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In economics, concerns have been raised in relation to the credibility and reliability of published research.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In other sciences, reproducibility is regarded as fundamental and is often a prerequisite to research being published, however in economic sciences it is not seen as a priority of the greatest importance.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Most peer-reviewed economic journals do not take any substantive measures to ensure that published results are reproducible, however, the top economics journals have been moving to adopt mandatory data and code archives.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] There is low or no incentives for researchers to share their data, and authors would have to bear the costs of compiling data into reusable forms.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Economic research is often not reproducible as only a portion of journals have adequate disclosure policies for datasets and program code, and even if they do, authors frequently do not comply with them or they are not enforced by the publisher.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] A Study of 599 articles published in 37 peer-reviewed journals revealed that while some journals have achieved significant compliance rates, significant portion have only partially complied, or not complied at all.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] On an article level, the average compliance rate was 47.5%; and on a journal level, the average compliance rate was 38%, ranging from 13% to 99%.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] A 2018 study published in the journal *PLOS ONE* found that 14.4% of a sample of public health statistics researchers had shared their data or code or both.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] There have been initiatives to improve reporting and hence reproducibility in the medical literature for many years, beginning with the CONSORT initiative, which is now part of a wider initiative, the EQUATOR Network.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] This group has recently turned its attention to how better reporting might reduce waste in research, especially biomedical research.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Reproducible research is key to new discoveries in pharmacology.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] A Phase I discovery will be followed by Phase II reproductions as a drug develops towards commercial production.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In recent decades Phase II success has fallen from 28% to 18%.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] A 2011 study found that 65% of medical studies were inconsistent when re-tested, and only 6% were completely reproducible.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Some efforts have been made to increase replicability beyond the social and biomedical sciences.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Studies in the humanities tend to rely more on expertise and hermeneutics which may make replicability more difficult.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Nonetheless, some efforts have been made to call for more transparency and documentation in the humanities.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Hideyo Noguchi became famous for correctly identifying the bacterial agent of syphilis, but also claimed that he could culture this agent in his laboratory.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Nobody else has been able to produce this latter result.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In March 1989, University of Utah chemists Stanley Pons and Martin Fleischmann reported the production of excess heat that could only be explained by a nuclear process ("cold fusion").
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The report was astounding given the simplicity of the equipment: it was essentially an electrolysis cell containing heavy water and a palladium cathode which rapidly absorbed the deuterium produced during electrolysis.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The news media reported on the experiments widely, and it was a front-page item on many newspapers around the world (see science by press conference).
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Over the next several months others tried to replicate the experiment, but were unsuccessful.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] Nikola Tesla claimed as early as 1899 to have used a high frequency current to light gas-filled lamps from over 25 miles (40 km) away without using wires.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] In 1904 he built Wardenclyffe Tower on Long Island to demonstrate means to send and receive power without connecting wires.
[src:dvc-versioning/reproducibility] The facility was never fully operational and was not completed due to economic problems, so no attempt to reproduce his first result was ever carried out.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:dvc-versioning/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
